Titles with Spaces — [[Double Bracket]] Rules

This is the single most common LLM mistake. Tiddler titles containing spaces MUST be wrapped in `[[double brackets]]` in most contexts. Without them, each word is treated as a separate title.

When brackets are REQUIRED:

- **Filter expressions**: `[title[My Tiddler]]` or `[[My Tiddler]]` — without brackets, `My` and `Tiddler` are separate filter runs
- **List fields** (tags, list): `[[Tag One]] [[Tag Two]]` — without brackets, this is 4 separate tags
- **`$list` filter parameter**: `filter="[[My Tiddler]]"` — bare `My Tiddler` is two separate titles
- **Tool calls** (`create_tiddler`, `set_field`, etc.): title parameter must be the exact title string, but any filter-based lookup needs brackets
- **`enlist` / `enlist-input`**: These split on spaces — `enlist[[My Tiddler]]` returns two items `My` and `Tiddler`
- **`tag[]` operator**: `[tag[My Tag]]` works (operator parameter is a single string), but listing results in a `tags` field needs brackets: `[[My Tag]] [[Other Tag]]`

When brackets are NOT needed:

- **Widget attributes**: `$tiddler="My Tiddler"` — quoted attributes are single strings
- **`title` field value**: `title: My Tiddler` in a `.tid` file — the field value is the entire line
- **`$action-navigate $to="My Tiddler"`** — widget attribute, not a filter
- **`{{My Tiddler!!field}}`** — transclusion syntax handles spaces (but `{{My Tiddler}}` without `!!field` is fine too)

Common mistakes:

```
<!-- BROKEN — opens "Project" and "Overview" as two tiddlers -->
<$action-navigate $to=Project Overview/>

<!-- CORRECT -->
<$action-navigate $to="Project Overview"/>

<!-- BROKEN — filter returns two items: "My" and "Tiddler" -->
[My Tiddler]

<!-- CORRECT -->
[[My Tiddler]]

<!-- BROKEN — tags field has 4 tags instead of 2 -->
tags: Tag One Tag Two

<!-- CORRECT -->
tags: [[Tag One]] [[Tag Two]]

<!-- BROKEN — enlist splits on spaces -->
<$list filter="[enlist[alpha beta My Tiddler]]">
<!-- produces: alpha, beta, My, Tiddler (4 items) -->

<!-- CORRECT — use enlist with proper bracketing -->
<$list filter="[enlist[alpha beta [[My Tiddler]]]]">
<!-- produces: alpha, beta, My Tiddler (3 items) -->
```

Best practice: When in doubt, ALWAYS use brackets around titles. `[[simple-title]]` works fine even when brackets aren't strictly needed.

Title naming conventions to avoid the problem:

- Use hyphens or slashes: `my-project-overview`, `projects/overview`
- Use CamelCase: `ProjectOverview`
- System tiddlers: `$:/config/my/setting` (no spaces)

---

Titles with `/` after a file extension break filesystem sync:

When a tiddler title appends `/child` to a title that ends with a file extension (e.g., `.pdf`), the filesystem adapter tries to create a directory where the file already exists. This causes `ENOTDIR` errors in a retry loop.

```
<!-- BROKEN — filesystem can't create report.pdf/extracted.tid because report.pdf is a file -->
My Report.pdf/extracted
My Report.pdf/summaries/model-timestamp

<!-- CORRECT — use dot instead of slash for child tiddlers of file-backed tiddlers -->
My Report.pdf.extracted
My Report.pdf.summaries/model-timestamp
```

This applies to any tiddler whose title matches a real file on disk (common with `_canonical_uri` tiddlers for uploaded files, PDFs, etc.).
